### Exercise 1

```{r exercise-1}

set.seed(123)

age <- rnorm(100, mean = 30, sd = 5)

df_colonists <- data.frame(
  id = 1:100, 
  age = age <- rnorm(100, mean = 30, sd = 5)
) 

roleD <- sample(c("engineer", "scientist", "medic"),
    replace = TRUE, 
    size = 100, prob = c(1,1,1)
)

```

1.2: The age distribution is normal, but there is more or less skew depending on the seed. For example, seed 123 is more negatively skewed, whereas seed 100 is more positively skewed. Seed 1000 is normally distributed though. 

1.3: I figured that all three roles are equally important and one should be as likely as the other but, realistically, they may get more people in one profession than another. Medics may want to live on mars more or less than a scientist. Randomness was my goal and, as such, I figured that randomly drawn roles with equal probability was the best option. I can see a world where getting an exact number of professionals is difficult. I think it would be fun to simulate this randomness to just see what happens. 

